taking time for myself has a really weird feeling. it’s been incredibly healing for myself but also can feel isolating at points in time. I think I have put this crazy pressure on myself to have it all figured out right now and being 25 has this pushing feeling of needing everything to start working perfectly — that’s not really necessary and also very important to sit down and see what you really want. This could be mind blowing to some but ~being in your mid 20’s is not “old”~ and makes me realize doing it all on my own maybe isn’t the way to go. I’ve been asking more and more questions, and I have been gaining more knowledge unbelievably fast from the questions i’m asking just because I am not afraid to ask. 🫶🏻 my alone time has been extremely humbling and also a huge learning curve in my own abilities.

Booked a ticket to Rome the night before in a bar after 2 girls I met in Croatia on my trip told me to come tag along with them🥹✈️ 
—
Rome was super overwhelming in great ways. I didn’t realize just how BIG Rome was! It was very crowded with a ton of people, but incredible history and everything was absolutely stunning around every corner, my jaw was dropped everywhere we went. 
— 
I would highly recommend getting an early start on your days when crowds aren’t as bad. We got up to see the Trevi Fountain at 5am and it was SO beautiful (especially with no crowds and only a few other people)! 
— 
Book tickets in advance, even on off season because the lines were still insane and booked up! Have fun✨🍝🫶🏻

I’ve moved so much in the past 2 years that I absolutely hated having “stuff” and “things” that weren’t my bed and basics. I traveled but didn’t want a random magnet or something i’ll forget about. Now i’m prioritizing things that are one of a kind and something i’ll keep forever and I know this one is eye catching… best perk? i’ll get to say ✨“oh that? I got it in ITALY!”✨

Advice for what clothes to bring on long trips 👙🧳👇🏼
- I ALWAYSSS pack outfits that match with each other. I can wear one outfit one day, then switch the pants out for another or vice versa. so you basically have double the outfits! 
- ALWAYS pack for the season. If I know it’s going to be insanely hot, I’m leaving the jeans at home. BUT it could be cold one or 2 days so i’ll also wear a jacket i’ll most likely wear on the plane as well. instead of wasting space in my bag, I can also tie around my waist. 
- What type of activities will you be doing? If i’m hiking or doing a lot outdoors i’m not going to be packing dresses lol. I always pack based around what we will be doing and sticking to that for the most part!
- What type of shoes do I pack? I usually bring 2 pairs of shoes on my trip. Depending on the weather and activities i’ll pack 2 completely different shoes that I can wear based on walking, night out shoes (I wear boots since they are versatile for daytime too) and leave the heels at home😭
🤝Being a light packer is a blessing BUT you can always use a laundromat or some hostels and hotels have laundry service as well! It will not be the end of the world if you have to post an instagram with the same outfit on twice ;)

travel has allowed me to become… me! I’ve learned so much about the world that nothing could’ve ever taught me besides first hand experience. I’ve met people from different cultures, backgrounds and countries, who spoke different languages than me but we could still communicate through other ways besides words. I’ve seen people show me things so important in their culture that i could’ve never known otherwise. I have had strangers invite me into their homes to feed me their food and let me sleep on their couches. I have not been judged, while they let me learn and become me by thriving through the hardship of maybe not speaking the language or getting lost in a foreign country. it sounds cheesy and can be scary at times, but man it is so beyond worth it. travel changes lives and i will always remember the memories i’ve had no matter where in the world. ✈️🌎🗺️ #adventuretravel

video by @kylegoesoff — I think my biggest lesson i’ve leaned over the last 5 years is to stop looking for a friend in everyone I meet. I know you may think “what do you mean? why is that bad?” I wouldn’t say “bad”, just quality over quantity. Repeat that in your head everyday. Make your existing friendships better and focus on those, unless you feel that those friendships aren’t serving you anymore. Don’t feel like every person you meet needs to be your bff, but also, if they make you feel that way, don’t fight that feeling! Love your friends and make sure they make you feel loved too. thank you @kylegoesoff, for getting this out of me.

Two years ago, I stepped foot across the pond in the UK, that would mark my first international trip ever, and be the catalyst for the love for travel that has since flipped my life upside down. 

It made me realize how much of the world there was to see and how far I can go!!!! 

This trip experience ignited a passion within me for learning more and traveling farther. I found that travel wasn't just about discovering new places; it was about discovering facets of myself I never knew existed. The journey became a reflection for everything in life to finding more and more about myself I didn’t know. 

Traveling is a commitment to growth, to breaking down the walls of comfort, and embracing the beauty of the world beyond your own culture.

Today, as I reflect on that pivotal trip, I'm grateful for the way it reshaped my perspective, expanded my horizons, and filled my heart with a journey that knows no bounds. Here's to the infinite possibilities that lie ahead of me, the amazing humans i’ve met along the way, (and the ones I haven’t met yet) and this beautiful world!!! CHEERS!!! 🌍 #womenwhotravel
